Shopify Earnings
----------------

From Bloomberg ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-02-15/shopify=
-sales-beat-analyst-estimates-as-recovery-gains-traction ) a couple of week=
s ago:

Shopify Inc. tumbled in after-hours trading after giving a sales outlook fo=
r the start of the year that fell short of analysts=E2=80=99 estimates, a s=
ign that it face an uneven recovery from last year=E2=80=99s rout. The Otta=
wa-based company said it expects first quarter revenue growth in the =E2=80=
=9Chigh teen percentages=E2=80=9D over last year, slightly below forecasts =
for 20% growth, according to a Bloomberg survey. Shopify said operating cos=
ts should grow in the low single digits compared with the fourth quarter, e=
xcluding one-time charges. The shares were down more than 11% in extended t=
rading at 6:08 p.m. in New York.

Chief Executive Officer Tobias L=C3=BCtke is working to recover from a misp=
laced bet that the pandemic-fueled surge in online shopping would become pe=
rmanent. Though he=E2=80=99s cut jobs, raised prices and expanded offerings=
 to merchants, the stock is a long way from a full recovery after losing ab=
out three-quarters of its value last year.

Analysts seemed fairly positive ( https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2=
023-02-16/shopify-analysts-shrug-off-weaker-outlook-while-stock-drops-16 ) =
on Shopify=E2=80=99s results, but I see a few reasons for concern above-and=
-beyond the company=E2=80=99s ongoing shift to lower margin businesses, par=
ticularly its fulfillment network, which was the biggest drag on profitabil=
ity last year. Specifically, I am a bit worried about saturation.

The first thing that jumped out to me on the company=E2=80=99s earnings cal=
l ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/4578803-shopify-inc-shop-q4-2022-earni=
ngs-call-transcript ) were the impending price hikes on Shopify=E2=80=99s l=
ower-level subscription plans. From President Harley Finkelstein=E2=80=99s =
prepared remarks:

In January, we announced an update to the subscription prices on our Basic,=
 Shopify and Advanced plans. The prices that we have been charging for acce=
ss to the best tools in commerce have largely remained unchanged for the la=
st 12 years. This will enable Shopify=E2=80=99s exceptional value to contin=
ue as we solve more of the most difficult problems in the industry and empo=
wer more people to become entrepreneurs. These new prices went into effect =
immediately for new merchants and will take effect on April 23 for existing=
 merchants.

Finkelstein expounded on this in the Q&A:

Our plan pricing has pretty much remained unchanged since I got here 13 yea=
rs ago. In the same time, we=E2=80=99ve added significant value to our subs=
cription offering to our merchants. We want to keep making commerce better =
in it. So I think the price increase reflects a fair value exchange, but it=
 also allows us to keep solving really, really tough problems and empower m=
ore people to become entrepreneurs.\

No price increase in 12 years is certainly a remarkable thing, and without =
question Finkelstein is correct that Shopify has dramatically increased the=
 value it provided for that unchanged price. That raises the question, thou=
gh, as to why Shopify never raised its prices.

The obvious answer is that while existing customers (which in the case of S=
hopify are merchants) may be more than willing to pay more, because they re=
cognize the value of what they are getting (and also don=E2=80=99t want to =
go to the hassle of changing platforms), new customers have not yet come to=
 appreciate that value, and higher prices is a deterrent to getting started=
. To put it another way, price elasticity for existing customers is differe=
nt than price elasticity for new customers; it follows, then, that a compan=
y focused first and foremost on acquiring new customers ought to care more =
about the price elasticity of those new customers, even if it means leaving=
 some money on the table in terms of existing customers.

This is obviously a somewhat simplistic view of the situation, particularly=
 as Shopify has created higher-level plans to both deliver and capture more=
 value to existing customers as their business grows, and has of course see=
n much more revenue growth in its Merchant Solutions business (i.e. Shopify=
 Payments in particular). Still, suspiciously low pricing for a very long t=
ime suggests that the business in question is primarily focused on expandin=
g their market; by extension, a price increase at least hints at the possib=
ility that the business in question believes its market is becoming saturat=
ed.

Shopify=E2=80=99s results suggest this is the case; year-over-year growth i=
n Subscription Solutions, which is a function of the number of merchants on=
 the platform as well as their pricing level, was in the teens, substantial=
ly lower than Merchant Solutions growth, which is a function of gross merch=
andise volume:

Of course the pandemic makes it hard to do year-over-year comparisons; here=
 are the comparisons to three-years ago:

There are other clues, as well: over the last year Shopify has rolled out s=
tarter plans ( https://www.shopify.com/starter ) for people looking to sell=
 a single product, and extended trials in Q3 of last year. That extended tr=
ial initiative, its worth noting, does suppress subscription growth, but it=
 would only have had an effect the last two quarters; what is more notable =
is that it exists. You can put a similar spin on initiatives around helping=
 merchants go global, both in terms of where they sell and also in terms of=
 where merchants are located; both are worthwhile initiatives, but both are=
 also the sort of initiatives you undertake when you start to suspect that =
your core market is increasingly saturated.

